{"_id":"XgtMIO05JAhEXG90","name":"[23] Villein (Mabisi of Clan Drebor)","content":"<p>A talented farmer with a substantial amount of land, forty serf acres and five free acres, Mabisi could have lived well through the last five years if he wasn’t so free with his food. As Clanhead, he supported several families, often leaving his wife, uncle and cousin on the verge of starvation themselves. For this, he is much beloved by his clan. A pragmatic man, he is willing to forget Akitt and work closely with a new bailiff for the good of his clan if he sees him as a just and fair lord.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":4600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Xqwk8LbewxpPnMhQ","name":"[19] Villein-Herder (Harquey of Clan Heryla)","content":"<p>The head of the largest clan in the village and also the herder, Harquey should be quite thankful, but he is not. Despite having enough food to spare for less fortunate clansmen, he was not able to save his first born son from being killed when a tree fell on him in the forest. He blames Arrel who put his son on an “easy” detail trimming branches from the trees after they were felled. His wife holds the household (including their younger son, her mother and two nieces) together.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":3800000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"YDVVHjGYY19cr5aj","name":"[M9] Palisade and Courtyard","content":"<h2>Palisade and courtyard</h2><p>When Sir Geleyn first became bailiff of Charmic Manor, there was quite a problem with wolves in the area. A large palisade, built of stout timbers and ten feet tall, was built to provide refuge for the villagers. After almost virtually eliminated the local wolf population, they replaced part of the wall with a low fence. Today fungus and rot have got into the wood and the whole thing could be knocked over with a stout kick.</p>\n<p>Since the arrival of Lord Akitt, several rotten sections of the palisade have collapsed and nothing has been done to repair them. The wolf population has bounced back and now the population no longer has anywhere to seek refuge. Three villagers were killed last winter and the villagers now close up their homes the best they can and huddle together when the wolves are on the hunt.</p>\n<p>The courtyard is a sea of mud and filth. Piles of rotting garbage and manure give it a disgusting reek. Large puddles of standing water mixed with animal urine dot the yard. The contents of the manor chamber pots have just been thrown in the corner of the palisade. The yard of the basest cottar is not this filthy.</p>\n","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":1800000},"cf":{"id":"temp_dn7blwley0v","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"ZPv9aupxzHWSBYcB","name":"[40] Half-Villein (Uldon of Clan Torlis)","content":"<p>Uldion works hard to support his family. His wife is a complainer and does little to help. The only good thing to come out of the famine is that she isn’t fat anymore. She sits and bitches with her two cousins who live with the couple. One of the women was quite friendly with Kenric the mercenary and now has two bastard children that Uldion must support as well.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":8000000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"ZmEliTNa7r9v7mPd","name":"Settlement Overview","content":"<h1>Settlement Overview</h1><p><strong>Location:</strong> Nephshire, Kingdom of Kaldor<br /><strong>Holder:</strong> Bailiff<br /><strong>Liege:</strong> Earl of Neph, Curo of Gardiren<br /><strong>Population:</strong> Village 194; Manor 7</p>\n<h2>Geographical Details</h2>\n<p>Charmic is a moderate sized fief in northern Kaldor, held as a personal fief by the Earl of Neph under a temporary bailiff, Sir Peart Tanush. The fief is only sixty-five years old, having been created by the previous Earl of Neph in 655TR as a new manor on which to settle a number of villeins from his other estates. Although located only five leagues south-east of Gardiren, Charmic is in a relatively isolated area, bounded on all sides by woods. The large Kirsta Forest to the south is a wild and forbidding place, full of wolves and brigands. The village sits next to a small stream which forms the boundary between Dobraine and Kirsta Hundreds. The manor is in a pleasant valley bottom with fine soil and moderate climate. All crops grow well and the estate has great potential.</p>\n<p>The manor is at the end of the road from Gardiren. There is substantial traffic on the road up to the quarry a half a league away. From there, the road turns into a narrow, muddy track. Those unfamiliar with the route to Charmic Manor might well think the road is a dead end. The only other road from Charmic leads east to Zernhol Manor. The people of Zernhol prefer to take the road via Erwund Abbey to Gardiren. The Laranian abbey is rich and powerful and their road is well maintained and patrolled. The woods around Charmic have a bad reputation.</p>\n<p>The bailiff owes the Earl £115 82d per year in feudal payments plus one Heavy Horse and four Light Foot. Due to the previous bailiff’s relationship to the Earl, the military obligation has been rendered as scutage (£7 48d per year). The manor has paid its full account of £122 130d each mid-summer’s day for the last five years.</p>\n<h2>History</h2>\n<p>Clan Morfan were made the Bailiffs of Charmic manor in 685TR. Originally a minor clan, their dedication and loyalty greatly impressed the Earl of Gardiren. Their leader, Sir Geleyn, was very devoted to his duties. He over saw the construction of a large and comfortable wooden manor house, a substantial palisade and several new buildings during his tenure as bailiff. With the Earl’s permission, he expanded the amount of cleared land and established over a dozen new households.</p>\n<p>Sir Geleyn was well liked by the tenants. He was a fair and just lord. He worked tirelessly to improve the manor and expected the same of his tenants. He was responsible for recruiting a metalsmith and woodcrafter to compliment the miller.</p>\n<p>An enthusiastic hunter, he and his three sons hunted out virtually all of the wolves and bears in the area, to the great relief of the peasants. His regular patrols discouraged bandits and brigands, while his efficient manor courts resolved most minor legal problems quickly and to the general satisfaction of the population.</p>\n<p>From 685 to 715TR, the manor grew significantly. Sir Geleyn was prompt with his feudal obligations (both military and financial) and the Earl’s Steward was much impressed, resulting in a steady rise of the status of Clan Morfan within Earl Curo’s court during those thirty years. Therefore, few were surprised when the Earl granted Umbrea and Warial manors to Clan Morfan in 715TR. These two manors had reverted back to the Earl on the death of the last member of the Clan Thuen and their award to Clan Morfan was seen as a reflection of the Earl’s satisfaction with their loyal performance as Bailiffs and their worthiness to be permanent landholders.</p>\n<p>During the summer of 715TR, Clan Morfan held a final manor court to say farewell to their tenants before leaving for Umbrea Manor. In addition to the departure of the family, they also took their men-at-arms and two yeomen families who followed them to their new holding.</p>\n<h2>The Bastard</h2>\n<p>The present Earl’s father was a man of lusty appetites, even in his later years. He fathered several bastards, including Akitt Llack. Akitt was acknowledged and lived with his mother in one of the Earl’s townhouses until the Earl died when he was twelve. His father’s widow hated him and ordered he and his mother immediately expelled from the only home he had ever known.</p>\n<p>On the death of the Earl’s widow a decade later, Akitt was brought back to court. With his mother dead, Earl Curo wanted to ensure his half-brother was taken care of, be he baseborn or no. However, the life of the timbewright’s apprentice had ill-prepared Akitt for the life at court and he soon made a fool of himself.</p>\n<p>Anxious to rid himself of an embarrassment, the Earl made Akitt bailiff of Charmic manor, a rich fief on the edge of his domain. Thinking he was being quite magnanimous, Curo sent Akitt off to the wilderness without recognizing the humiliation, rage and hate boiling in his veins.</p>\n<h2>The Dark Years</h2>\n<p>Akitt’s arrival in Charmic was unremarkable. He came with only a couple of men-at-arms (mercenaries) and his cousin Lynd (a timberwright). This was a far cry from the large household previously supported by the Clan Morfan.</p>\n<p>Within a week, the peasants began to sense things were going to change. Almost immediately, Lynd began to explore the area, looking at stands of timber. When he began to blaze large oaks in the King’s forest (outside of the manor boundaries), the Woodward, Muir, became quite concerned and went to the new Bailiff. Far from supporting the Woodward’s concerns, Akitt became extremely angry and told Muir that if he ever questioned Lynd’s again, he would be beaten. The two mercenaries then threw Muir out of the hall.</p>\n<p>The next rest day, Akitt summoned Witol the Reeve. He informed him that the King had granted him the right to as many oaks as he wished from unsettled land. He held up a writ with many seals and signatures in front of the illiterate man and told him that Lynd had already marked out the first trees to be cut.</p>\n<p>For the rest of the summer and through the fall, the villagers cut trees. A new road was cleared, but the people were suspicious when they were ordered to only cut the largest trees, and never ones visible from the fields or road. The trees were felled and the logs transported to a new cutting yard, built in the middle of the village. The villagers spent many days cutting the logs into beams under the direction of Lynd, a ruthless task master.</p>\n<p>So much logging was being done that normal fief maintenance suffered. Again, Witol approached Lord Akitt. He asked the bailiff to give him enough men to do normal repairs to the manor, roads and fences. He was flatly denied and was barely allowed enough men and time to bring in the harvest. Despite the lack of maintenance, Lord Akitt took every fee and tax he was due.</p>\n<p>Wagons from the timberwright’s guild were regular visitors to the manor. The guildsmen were welcomed warmly by Lord Akitt and Lynd and many lavish feasts were held for them. Lord Akitt dismissed most of the staff who had worked for Sir Geleyn, but the few remaining servants reported that the guild master gave Lord Akitt many heavy pouches that he kept a large iron-bound chest in his room. The Bailiff kept the only key around his neck at all times.</p>\n<p>Normally, winter is a time of rest for the peasants. The first winter under the new Bailiff was a rude change. Lynd drove the men mercilessly. Up before dawn for the long walk out to the logging area, the men worked right until last light before returning, exhausted, to their homes. The constant heavy labour left the men hungry. Under the rule of Clan Morfan, the men could have at least expected a good meal in the manor hall, but under Lord Akitt, they were left to live off of their own meagre stores of food. By spring, all of the households were hungry and short of food. Starvation was only averted by an early spring.</p>\n<p>As expected, the winter took a toll on the manor. With the coming of spring, Witol the Reeve again approached the Lord with plans to repair the winter damage and catch up on the maintenance that had not been done the previous fall. This time, for questioning the Bailiff’s priorities, Witol was beaten by the men-at-arms for his insolence and driven from the hall. Immediately following the completion of spring planting and a bare minimum of other vital tasks, the men were again ordered to return to logging.</p>\n<p>The pattern of ignoring fief maintenance and using every spare man to log the King’s forest continued for five years. In 717, Lord Akitt sacked the Reeve and replaced him with Jodoin, a cowardly yes-man who gladly enforced the Bailiff’s every command without question. Witol, who had so loyally served the Clan Morfan for thirty years, was stripped of his land when his son tried to run away. The boy was dragged back and cruelly beaten. He never recovered and died the following winter. Witol was reduced from villein to cottar and now struggles to feed his wife and remaining son.</p>\n<p>Throughout this time, Akitt and his cousin got richer and richer, filling the first chest and adding two more. Each year, the tenants hoped and prayed that the Earl’s Steward come to Charmic and discover Lord Akitt’s cruel actions and remove him. He never arrived. Little did they know that the Bailiff faithfully paid the Earl exactly the same payments as Clan Morfan had for the last thirty years, and so the Steward saw no need to check up on the Earl’s own half-brother.</p>\n<p>The harvest of 719TR was very bad. Despite this, Lord Akitt took his full share (most of which he sold at a handsome profit), leaving virtually nothing for the peasants. Faced with starving parishioners, Charmic’s Peonian priest could take no more and slipped away in the night to take word to the Earl. After walking all day, the priest arrived at the Earl’s castle in the middle of a feast. He convinced the guard to call the Steward out of the hall and informed him what was happening. When the Steward relayed the news to the Earl he summoned the village priest before him, questioning him in detail. Then, the Earl summoned the local Peonian priest from Gardiren to confirm the man was indeed from Charmic. Determined to convince the Earl, the village priest fell to his knees and swore a holy vow on the sacred relic of Peoni. Convinced by the man’s honesty, Earl Curo was furious and declared “the ungrateful wretch”, Akitt Llack, outlaw.</p>\n<p>As he hurried through the town of Gardiren, the village priest was recognized by one of Akitt’s “business partners”, Naviel, who realized they would all hang when the Earl found out what was happening. Naviel rode to Charmic to warn Akitt while the Earl was busy interrogating the priest. In a flurry of activity, the bailiff, his halfbrother, two mercenary guards and Naviel rode out of Charmic in the middle of the night, only hours ahead of the Earl’s guards.</p>\n<p>None of the five men have been seen since. Earl Curo has posted a large reward for the capture of these men so he can try them for corruption and theft. They also face Royal charges of theft, for cutting the King’s trees without leave.</p>\n<h2>Current Affairs</h2>\n<p>The corrupt bailiff, Akitt Llack, is gone. The Earl has sent a temporary bailiff, Sir Peart Tanush, and five men-atarms to secure the manor and to salvage what can be salvaged. Sir Peart has temporarily relieved the tenants of all other duties but their work in the fields in hope of producing enough food so the villagers can survive the winter. He is taking stock of the manor house and other improvements on the fief. What he sees is not good. Once the harvest is secure, he will make what temporary repairs he can.</p>\n<p>Sir Peart has made a preliminary report to the Earl. He has recommended that a new permanent bailiff be appointed as soon as possible. He recommended it be a man of action, as there is much work to be done. Currently secured by Sir Peart and his men, the village is safe, but the woods are filled with outlaws and wolves are roaming the manor by night. Several villagers have been attacked even within the limits of the village itself. The new bailiff will need to hunt down these wolves and put an end to the outlaws, not a task for a bureaucrat.</p>\n<p>Whoever takes on the job will have a great deal of maintenance to catch up on and hostile villager’s to deal with. However, a skilful negotiator may be able to win concessions from the Earl, such as relief from feudal payments for a few years, to help pay for the repairs.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":400000}}}
{"_id":"aNx2DdHeSk7wAnQu","name":"[C] Village Common","content":"<h2>Village Common</h2><p>The area in front of the manor house is reserved for a gathering area for the villagers. It was rarely used during Lord Akitt’s reign, except when he called the peasants together to threaten them.</p>\n","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_7b68j8e8k4","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"bB9oYObq3tW3aizm","name":"[37] Woodcrafter (Aenan of Clan Korien)","content":"<p>Size: 2 Quality: ★★★★ Price: Very low</p>\n<p>Aenan and his apprentice were brought to Charmic by Clan Morfan in 714 to build a new barn and manor house. When the Morfans were awarded their own manor, they assured him that the new bailiff would still need his services. Akitt did, as a junior journeyman and serf to his cousin, Lynd the timberwright. Aenan refused to stand for the insult and announced he was leaving immediately. That night he received a visit from Brilan and his brothers (@Compendium[hm-loc-charmic.journals.cOlzvx74stvPYNHv]{[11] Cottar (Brilan of Clan Kyfa)}). After they ransacked the house, they held his newborn son over the fire and told him he wasn’t going anywhere. For the next five years, one of Akitt’s lackeys was always watching him and his family. Aenan has already demanded an audience with Sir Peart to claim damages and travelled to Gardiren to lodge a formal complaint with his guild. Strangely, his wife has grown to love the people of the village and wouldn’t consider leaving.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":7400000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"c7AbapHmTgtRfjXX","name":"[1] Cottar (Girn of Clan Valada)","content":"<p>Girn is married. With only two acres, there is no way he can feed his wife and himself. In desperation, he has reluctantly become one of Akitt’s enforcers. Even selling himself, they have barely enough to eat. The couple’s home is little more than a cave built of rocks and thatch. The couple’s one son was taken by wolves in 719TR while checking on the family pig in a pen behind the house.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":200000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"cOlzvx74stvPYNHv","name":"[11] Cottar (Brilan of Clan Kyfa)","content":"<p>Clan Kyfa are newcomers to Charmic. They were brought here by Lord Akitt. The family head is Brilan, a former teamster from Gardiren. He and his four brothers were responsible for transporting the timber from the manor to the buyers. They asked no questions, even when the deliveries were made in the middle of the night. Hard men, they are familiar with cudgels and staffs and are not afraid to use them. After Kenric and Hedin (the two mercenaries) they are the most feared men in the village. With the departure of their patron and protector, the six men stay close to their wives and Brilan’s infant son. They are ready to flee if necessary.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":2200000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"ek7uTNuqNCJkW7zm","name":"[34] Half-Villein (Ulyn of Clan Ailt)","content":"<p>Although food is sometimes short, Ulyn’s house is one tiny glimmer of joy in this otherwise grey village. Two months ago his wife gave birth to a brand new baby boy. The women of the clan have come together to make sure both mother and baby have enough to eat. In return, Ulyn and his half-brother and nephew have worked extra hours at the sawpit to allow other men time in the fields.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":6800000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"gp7NYpWAdBb5JCXj","name":"[20] Cottar (Arsain of Clan Torlis)","content":"<p>Arsain is the village healer. During the last five years, he has spent more time comforting those dying of starvation rather than healing them. Five times, he collected poisonous plants to give to the manor cook to kill the hated Lord Akitt and five times his strong Peonian morals stopped him. He supports his wife and mother. He is the brother of Aslen (@Compendium[hm-loc-charmic.journals.Vr0Ph882teu5FxDo]{[28] Cottar (Aslen of Clan Torlis)}).</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":4000000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"hUrOCmU9nQFTp7V9","name":"[T3] Drying House","content":"<p>This open faced shed is used to season the timber before sale. Most of the wood is in the form of large timbers cut from the heart of the tree. The rounded pieces left from this process are then cut into planks. Every few months, guildsmen would come and take stock of the available timbers and buy what they needed. Sir Peart has impounded this timber in the name of the King.</p>\n\n","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_frexav32o9u","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"iTcrRooRWGqLE0OC","name":"[8] Yeoman (MF) (Soben of Clan Heryla)","content":"<p>Soben likes to talk tough, but he is afraid to follow through. Once, when his back was to the door, Akitt walked in and caught him plotting to escape. The bailiff didn’t punish him; instead he handed Soben’s teenage daughter over to his mercenaries for a night and warned him that his eight year old daughter would be next if he ever tried anything else. Soben supports his wife, two daughters, grandson (from the rape) and a cousin. When Akitt said jump, Soben obeyed.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":1600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"ixxuVoZ8qJT7SLKn","name":"[39] Villein (Arge of Clan Kralis)","content":"<p>Despite loosing several Clan members to starvation, Arge and his wife have come through the hard times relatively well. Their children were all grown before Akitt arrived and so were able to help during the lean years. Arge still supports his wife, two sons, one daughter, her husband and a four year old granddaughter. The girl is constantly ill and has broken several bones already in her young life. Arge is clan head of Clan Kralis.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":7800000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"m2FprhjCX1XAG2Cq","name":"[T1] Tool Shed","content":"<h2>Tool Shed</h2><p>This building was used for the storage and maintenance of Lynd’s tools. Axes, saws, chisels and other tools are carefully stored on well built racks on the walls. The floor is packed earth, but is clean and recently swept. Good, dry scrap wood has been stacked in the corner to keep it out of the weather.</p>\n","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":200000},"cf":{"id":"temp_frexav32o9u","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"mDUjcXS48mIHEPrr","name":"[26] Villein (Baralis of Clan Torlis)","content":"<p>A successful farmer and head of his clan, Baralis is not a popular man. He hoards food, sharing nothing with the less fortunate members of his clan. His mother, wife and two sons are well fed and strong. He believes only the strong (or in this case, those with land) will survive. He cares nothing for the suffering of others.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":5200000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"mmJU8YZN4gJtuprU","name":"[B] Manor Wood Lot","content":"<h2>Manor Wood Lot</h2><p>This is the eastern edge of the wood lot that Akitt is allowed to log. It is largely untouched.</p>\n","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":400000},"cf":{"id":"temp_7b68j8e8k4","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"nRup6IVmzYteGl7e","name":"[12] Half-Villein (Virisla of Clan Heryla)","content":"<p>Virisla has a dark secret. During the worst of the famine, while his wife slept, he took his son and daughter (who were starving and weak from fever) into the graveyard and strangled them rather than watch them die slowly. He then buried them. When his wife awoke, he told her that they had died in the night. His wife does not believe him and refuses to let him touch her. She sleeps with her sister, brother-in-law and two nieces at the other end of the cottage. Virisla is racked with guilt and is contemplating suicide.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":2400000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"nUnKGuBL4ssHx34j","name":"[M8] Main Hall","content":"<h2>Main Hall</h2><p>This is a large timber-frame building on a stone foundation. It has a slate roof, which needs repairs in several locations and leaks badly over the front door when it rains. The solar and one-quarter of the main hall are paved with large flat flagstones, a project begun under the Clan Morfan. A stack of unused flagstones are piled outside the back of the hall where they have sat since 715TR. The room is dominated by a large central hearth; smoke filters out through a covered opening in the roof directly above the fire pit. The building has not been whitewashed in several years and some of the daub is beginning to flake off.</p>\n<p>The solar was used by Lord Akitt and his guests. The two additional beds and crib date from the previous residents, probably the same time the sheets were last washed. There are outlines in the grime where three chests once stood.</p>\n","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":1600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_dn7blwley0v","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"nYObOPamI3gB9jAa","name":"[H] Road to Umbrea Manor","content":"<h2>Road to Umbrea Manor</h2><p>This is the main road to the manor. The lane leads straight into Gardiren just five leagues away.</p>\n","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":1600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_7b68j8e8k4","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"owFvdvrbdDQzJT6N","name":"[38] Villein (Koman of Clan Torlis)","content":"<p><img style=\"width:35%;float:left;margin-right:5px\" src=\"modules/hm-loc-charmic/assets/images/koman-of-torlis.webp\" /></p>\n<p>Koman is forty-three years old and an adopted member of Clan Torlis. He came to the village thirty-nine years ago in the care of an old man and woman. He grew up and married into the clan and he and his wife have two grown sons, one of whom is married. Koman also supports two of his wife’s sisters. Unknown to all but Koman, he is actually from Rethem. He is the bastard son of Kedrel Norgalen and Tamasyne Lerek and has letters of acknowledgement and a number of strange artefacts in an iron box buried under his bed. He was spirited out of kingdom by loyal servants of his father to escape the clutches of Regent Puril. Koman has no desire to resurrect this past, but he was trained with a sword in secret as a young man and will fight to protect his family. He is Peonian.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":7600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"p907Sny2cwX9yQwG","name":"[17] Cottar (Seld of Clan Sarion)","content":"<p>Seld is the sole survivor of his once thriving household of eight. With only three acres he was forced to watch first his parents and then his children fade away. His wife was killed by wolves last winter as she collected drop wood in the manor wood lot. He would kill Akitt if he got the chance. He will gladly help anyone pursuing the bailiff.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":3400000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
