{"_id":"xTWzCyUuF064AGCm","name":"[4] Half-Villein (Umis of Clan Kralis)","content":"<p>Strong constitutions and a ruthless family head, Umis, have kept this large family together and alive. His mother, three brothers, one sister, wife and two teenage daughters all work extremely hard, eking every possible bit of food out of their garden and eleven acres. All four brothers are talented trappers and their poaching is all that has kept body and soul together for the last five years.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":800000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"xW6OQs7zirabpmr4","name":"[27] Cottar (Undryn of Clan Ailt)","content":"<p>Another widower, Undryn buried his wife and two children the first winter of Akitt’s reign of terror. He is little more than a shell now. Father Perras watches over him and make sure he eats. He has little will to live.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":5400000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"xgZPCm7hGQ4YKzG2","name":"[T2] Timberwright’s House","content":"<h2>Timberwright’s House</h2><p>This fine, comfortable house was the home of Lynd, Lord Akitt’s cousin. He forced the woodcrafter and villagers to help him build it. It is the finest house on the manor. It is tended by Lynd’s former apprentice, Thales, a fine young lad from Gardiren. He was not involved in the pillaging of the manor and was equally badly treated by the two men. He is well liked by the villagers. After Akitt and Lynd fled, he remained and tidied up the house, expecting his master to return. Instead, Sir Peart Tanush, deputy Steward of Earl Curo, and five men-at-arms arrived. Appalled by the state of the manor house, he chose to set up residence here. The deputy Steward is currently taking stock of the manor. Impressed by the young apprentice, he has allowed him to stay on as a domestic until the fate of Charmic is decided.</p>\n","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":400000},"cf":{"id":"temp_frexav32o9u","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"xwcD6712oKdxZPT9","name":"Charmic Village","content":"<p><img style=\"width:100%\" src=\"modules/hm-loc-charmic/assets/images/charmic-village.webp\" /></p>\n<p>Charmic village is a fair sized community. It has fortyone households consisting of 34 unfree serfs (13 villeins, 9 half-villeins, and 12 cottars), one free farmer, three guildsmen, two yeomen and one priest of Peoni.</p>\n<p>The village grew up along the main road. The Peonian church was built later and now the village is expanding along the road to the mill. The square is the centre of the village and the two of the guildsmen have their homes opening onto it. The mill is a rare Kaldoric example of a wind powered mill. Wind power was chosen due to the unpredictable volume of water in the stream and the steady breeze that always flows down the valley. The manor house is built along the banks of the stream and a moat, now rather silted, encircles it.</p>\n<p>The community consists of six main clans and a number of individual families. Lord Akitt used the clan ties to great effect, meting out punishments against the whole clan to force them to keep their own members in line. Few will runaway or rebel when their aunt or grandmother will be killed in retribution. Those without clan ties were even more vulnerable as they had no one to turn to for assistance or support. Most ended up becoming yes-men and lackeys for Lord Akitt out of shear survival. The three craftsmen (miller, metalsmith and woodcrafter) would normally have been safe from the worst excesses of the lord of the manor, but Akitt was ruthless to the point of demanding hostages every time they left the manor. He also sent one of his lackeys along with them to report their every move. Lord Akitt and his men kept a tight rein on everything that happened in the village, including killing one boy and taking the arm of his father for standing up to them.</p>\n<h2>Economics and Agrarian Life</h2>\n<p>Northern Kaldor has been settled since the days of the Kingdom of Serelind. However, this manor is relatively new and is still being developed. Charmic has 2060 gross acres, 432 wooded, leaving 1628 cleared acres. Of this, 799 acres support tenants and 829 acres are demesne. Prior to the arrival of Lord Akitt, this was an very productive fief, as it sits on rich alluvial topsoil.</p>\n<p>The manor is extremely rundown. The peasants have been taxed and worked to the very limit. The manor buildings require a long list of repairs. The fief itself requires a lot of work. The roads are badly rutted and barely passable. The recent lack of maintenance and general neglect has greatly reduced its productivity. Under the rule of Clan Morfan, the manor had a fief index of 1.10. Under Lord Akitt, that value fell to 0.85, a sign of serious neglect.</p>\n<p>The manor demesne used to support a large herd of cattle and sheep, but Lord Akitt sold them off as being too labour intensive. The cattle herd has dwindled to just twelve cows and one, rather old, bull. The sheep herd is also down, though the price of wool convinced Akitt to keep forty sheep and five rams. Starvation and high taxes have thinned the numbers of villager’s animals almost to nothing. A few pigs and one or two jealously protected goats are all that remain. The people of the village are generally thin and malnourished, with a few notable exceptions, mostly Akitt’s lackeys. The villagers are downtrodden and will not meet the eye of a noble or anyone else in authority.</p>\n<p>A side effect of the starvation is fewer children or old people. Most of them died off during a series of hard winters with little or no food and the bad harvest in the fall of 719TR. The villagers hope that a new lord will find some way to get them through the winter, but it has been long since they had any hope. A new lord will have to work hard to earn their trust.</p>","img":"modules/hm-loc-charmic/assets/images/charmic-village.webp","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"y3xOdo1SN5UGU0Kw","name":"[13] Cottar (Ailarn of Clan Heryla)","content":"<p>Ailarn never married. He lives with his mother in a small cottage. She works their garden plot and he toils at the timberwright’s yard. He has become more adept at stealing vegetables from other villager’s plots and hiding his tracks since being beaten unconscious by his cousin Weryn (@Compendium[hm-loc-charmic.journals.P2oup74n6LQlJ49K]{[6] Yeoman (MF) (Weryn of Clan Ailt)}) last autumn.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":2600000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"zQr2GWfg68e9C9UR","name":"[41] Farmer (Nae of Clan Sarion)","content":"<p>Aside from the yeomen, Nae is the only free farmer in the village. Because of this, he was able to avoid most of the problems faced by the rest of the village. An excellent farmer, he was easily able to support his wife and himself on their ten acres. He saw early what was going on and was smart enough to send his sons to find work in Gardiren. He has two strapping lads who would be willing to move back to Charmic if there were any decent prospects.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"PusKspNsRtwjEZQs":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":8200000},"cf":{"id":"temp_vp55g1baur9","color":"#000000"}}}
